1 adult leg banded. Sheltering on N end of East shore.  Location 37°52'29.3"N 122°19'03.8"W  Structurally,  a loon. -- Floating on water, more like a PBGR in shape than a duck or goose, and with a much more acute bill angle. Gray/brown overall with a white breast and belly. Reddish throat patch. Gray neck and head with wavy white streaks on a black field beginning at back of head and continuing down the back of the neck to the scapulars. The black/white appearance of the streaks dissolve into a sparser pattern black on a white background as the marks continue around the neck to the throat. The gray front of the throat is gray with reddish throat patch, both terminating in a clearly demarcated line across the throat as the upper boundary of the aforementioned black on white pattern of the lower throat and upper breast. The one leg seen has a USGS band on it. The leg is anchored at the extreme rear of the belly. The foot is webbed and patterned pink, black and white. Eye is red.   The primaries presented crisp pale tips crossing over the rump.

In size, behavior, and most plumag identical to the American GEWE. Lacks the vertical white stripe at front of chest and does have a horizontal white stripe above flank. Buff line above green face mark and white line below.  This is possibly an intergrade or, as ebird.org would have it, a hybrid.   Note the interrupted white vertical stripe on the side. Sometimes a ruffled feather or leucism can lead to this appearance but in this case it seems more likely to be an undisturbed normal and natural feather. I was not close enough to gather a DNA sample.

After much discussion with Stephen Fettig and Joe Fitzgibbon, ID was agreed. Note in particular the facial pattern including the full white line above the bill. This makes it not a LAWO but one of the two sapsuckers with a similar facial pattern, the RNSA and YBSA. Spots on the head rule out RNSA and rule in the YBSA. The YBSA can maintain juvenal plumage in early winter but the RNSA would have molted all of its juvenal plumage by now. A further separator is the all pale plumage of the belly in YBSA vs. speckled belly of the RNSA juvenile. Why no white wing patch? This from Stephen Fettig explains: When sapsuckers get cold they seem to not show the white in the wing because the back feathers fluff-up and cover the wings more than in warmer times. I remember this from other sapsuckers I have photographed in the winter. So the lack of white in the wing is not an issue -- for me. Photos by Dave Yeamans. (additional photos at http://ebird.org/ebird/edit/checklist?subID=S16302018 )

Several heard. Two seen, a male red-shafted and a female intergrade. The under wing of the female intergrade was not orange but it wasn't all that yellow either. I'm inclined to call it flicker, intergrade, northern for the following reasons.  FLIN description for observation 2017-10-06 Del Valle Regional Park, Alameda County, California   09:41 a.m., forest shade on an open fire road with north-facing slope in a canyon, i.e. fair to good  light for visual observation and photos. No wind; full alto-cirrus sky.   The FLIN and one or more NOFL (the NOFL is clearly red-shafted based on nape, face, and head plumage [see photo]) were foraging on the roadway about 50 feet from me. I had noticed “these” birds an hour earlier as I hiked up the road and was keen to find them again, which I did as I returned to the location.   Two photos below show a flicker with no malar mark, hence, female. A red “nape crescent” is visible but this is much diminished from what I typically see on the yellow-shafted (I seek expert opinion on this YSFL mark, and yet I have extensive close up experience — photos on request — with this mark in the FLIN of New Mexico).   My attention was drawn to this bird by the not-very-orange but not-quite-yellow under wing coloration in flight. The photos do not show shaft colors, but they do show head color patterns that indicate RSFL. The face is gray and the crown is brown, clearly demarcated from each other. Sibley (Second Edition, Third Printing p. 320)** points out this mark for RSFL but exactly the opposite for YSFL. Interestingly, the head pattern for gilded flicker is an exact match for the bird shown in the photos. That match could indicate a third genotype present or a clinal variation among three varieties of Colaptes.  So here we have a NOFL with the clearly visible head pattern of a RSFL (or GIFL) but with the nape pattern of a YSFL . It also has (not photographed but true, based on the observer’s senses) racis coloration intermediate between YSFL and RSFL. The nomenclature of Flicker, Intergrade Northern  seems appropriate but not definitive. (OPINION: THE FLIN nomenclature seems more descriptive than Colaptes sp. which would imply a weaker observation or analysis.)     ** See also National Wildlife Federation, 2007, and National Geographic, Fifth edition.

Compare these photos with those of Hutton's vireo in this same checklist: remarkably similar.

Location 37°52'29.3"N 122°19'03.8"W  Structurally,  a loon. -- Floating on water, more like a PBGR in shape than a duck or goose, and with a much more acute bill angle. Gray/brown overall with a white breast and belly. Reddish throat patch. Gray neck and head with wavy white streaks on a black field beginning at back of head and continuing down the back of the neck to the scapulars. The black/white appearance of the streaks dissolve into a sparser pattern black on a white background as the marks continue around the neck to the throat. The gray front of the throat is gray with reddish throat patch, both terminating in a clearly demarcated line across the throat as the upper boundary of the aforementioned black on white pattern of the lower throat and upper breast. The one leg seen has a USGS band on it. The leg is anchored at the extreme rear of the belly. The foot is webbed and patterned pink, black and white. Eye is red.   The primaries presented crisp pale tips crossing over the rump.

Empid, mostly gray, so not PSFL. Eye ring round, not tear drop shaped. The only empids in this area to confuse it with would be GRFL and PSFL. Nevertheless, those two and DUFL are ruled out by foraging, flying, and perching behavior. Most noticeable is a total lack of tail motion soon after landing. Then it flicked its wings which neither of the other two do regularly.  Not that it matters for this ID, but to further separate this bird from Dusky (a foolproof method if you are sure you have one or the other) is to look at the first photo. Notice the overlap in the primaries, and how there is a great asymmetry in the gaps between the longest p-feathers. Dusky has no such asymmetry, all the gaps are the same. Also note how much rump is showing which gives the wings a distinct angle where the primaries meet the secondaries.  Photo 3 is a good illustration of how and why the HAFL (and DUFL and GRFL and probably many more empids) can show much more or less yellow in the breast. The insulating feathers are yellowish and the contour feathers are grayish.

Media notes: Intergrade. Reduced nape crescent. Best view of gray face with brown cap (reversed from YSFL)
Observation Details: Several heard. Two seen, a male red-shafted and a female intergrade. The under wing of the female intergrade was not orange but it wasn't all that yellow either. I'm inclined to call it flicker, intergrade, northern for the following reasons.  FLIN description for observation 2017-10-06 Del Valle Regional Park, Alameda County, California   09:41 a.m., forest shade on an open fire road with north-facing slope in a canyon, i.e. fair to good  light for visual observation and photos. No wind; full alto-cirrus sky.   The FLIN and one or more NOFL (the NOFL is clearly red-shafted based on nape, face, and head plumage [see photo]) were foraging on the roadway about 50 feet from me. I had noticed “these” birds an hour earlier as I hiked up the road and was keen to find them again, which I did as I returned to the location.   Two photos below show a flicker with no malar mark, hence, female. A red “nape crescent” is visible but this is much diminished from what I typically see on the yellow-shafted (I seek expert opinion on this YSFL mark, and yet I have extensive close up experience — photos on request — with this mark in the FLIN of New Mexico).   My attention was drawn to this bird by the not-very-orange but not-quite-yellow under wing coloration in flight. The photos do not show shaft colors, but they do show head color patterns that indicate RSFL. The face is gray and the crown is brown, clearly demarcated from each other. Sibley (Second Edition, Third Printing p. 320)** points out this mark for RSFL but exactly the opposite for YSFL. Interestingly, the head pattern for gilded flicker is an exact match for the bird shown in the photos. That match could indicate a third genotype present or a clinal variation among three varieties of Colaptes.  So here we have a NOFL with the clearly visible head pattern of a RSFL (or GIFL) but with the nape pattern of a YSFL . It also has (not photographed but true, based on the observer’s senses) racis coloration intermediate between YSFL and RSFL. The nomenclature of Flicker, Intergrade Northern  seems appropriate but not definitive. (OPINION: THE FLIN nomenclature seems more descriptive than Colaptes sp. which would imply a weaker observation or analysis.)     ** See also National Wildlife Federation, 2007, and National Geographic, Fifth edition.

Media notes: This is about a third of the terns in the naked eye view. Estimate rejected by ebird reviewer.
Observation Details: A truly remarkable number. The elegant tern photo of highest density shows about 375 birds by exact count of one grid rectangle multiplied by the number of grids (4 to be exact). It's less than a third of the total based on my estimation, from having been there and taking the photo. 3 x 375 = 1125 terns. Divide this computation by a cluelessness factor of 1.875 (roughly half) and you come out to 600 terns. This is in line with the estimate given recently by FWS personnel who have been monitoring the Elegant Tern.

After much discussion with Stephen Fettig and Joe Fitzgibbon, ID was agreed. Note in particular the facial pattern including the full white line above the bill. This makes it not a LAWO but one of the two sapsuckers with a similar facial pattern, the RNSA and YBSA. Spots on the head rule out RNSA and rule in the YBSA. The YBSA can maintain juvenal plumage in early winter but the RNSA would have molted all of its juvenal plumage by now. A further separator is the all pale plumage of the belly in YBSA vs. speckled belly of the RNSA juvenile. Why no white wing patch? This from Stephen Fettig explains: When sapsuckers get cold they seem to not show the white in the wing because the back feathers fluff-up and cover the wings more than in warmer times. I remember this from other sapsuckers I have photographed in the winter. So the lack of white in the wing is not an issue -- for me. Photos by Dave Yeamans. (additional photos at http://ebird.org/ebird/edit/checklist?subID=S16302018 )
